          "title": "CHAPTER 3 The Energy Theory of Cooking “A man does not live",
          "content": "CHAPTER 3: The Energy Theory of Cooking\n\"An old saying goes, 'A person does not live on what they eat, but on what they digest.'\" —Jean Anthelme Brillat-Savarin, The Physiology of Taste\nIn this chapter, we explore an interesting idea: that cooking food might actually help us get more energy from it. Research has shown that both animals and humans often gain weight and have better chances of having babies when they eat cooked food instead of raw food. This raises a fascinating question: Does cooking make food more nutritious and energy-rich?\nWhen we cook food, it can change its structure and make it easier for our bodies to digest. This means that we might be able to absorb more nutrients and calories from cooked food than from raw food. However, not everyone agrees with this idea. Some scientists and researchers have studied this topic and found that the relationship between cooking and energy is more complex than it seems.\nTo help us understand the nutrients in our food, we can look at important resources like the U.S. Department of Agriculture's National Nutrient Database. This database provides valuable information about the nutritional content of thousands of foods available in the United States. Similarly, in the United Kingdom, Robert McCance and Elsie Widdowson created a resource called The Composition of Foods, which serves a similar purpose. These databases are essential for helping us learn about what we eat and how cooking might change the nutritional value of our meals.\nIn summary, while cooking may help us gain more energy from our food, the science behind it is still being explored. Understanding how cooking affects our diets is crucial for making healthy choices and appreciating the role of cooking in our lives. As we continue to study this topic, we can learn more about how to prepare food in ways that maximize its benefits for our health and well-being.\nContext recap: CHAPTER 3: The Energy Theory of Cooking\n\"An old saying goes, 'A person does not live on what they eat, but on what they digest.'\" —Jean Anthelme Brillat-Savarin, The Physiology of Taste\nIn this chapter, we explore an interesting idea: that cooking food might actually help us get more energy from it. Research has shown that both animals and humans often gain weight and have better chances of having babies when they eat cooked food instead of raw food. This raises a fascinating question: Does cooking make food more nutritious and energy-rich? When we cook food, it can change its structure and make it easier for our bodies to digest.\nWhy this matters: CHAPTER 3 The Energy Theory of Cooking “A man does not live helps learners in Anthropology connect ideas from Catching Fire: How Cooking Made Us Human to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
