          "id": "cf-l06-c2",
          "title": "EPILOGUE The Well-Informed Cook Cooking launched a dietary c",
          "content": "EPILOGUE: The Well-Informed Cook. Cooking has played a crucial role in shaping our diets and has led to the development of a large food industry. Many of the popular foods that are made in big factories today often receive criticism because they tend to be low in important nutrients and high in unhealthy ingredients like fat, salt, and sugar. Even though these foods are often looked down upon, they are actually what our bodies have learned to crave over time. This situation has resulted in many people eating more than what is healthy for them. By the early 2000s, studies showed that around 61% of Americans were considered overweight, which can lead to various health problems. The easy access to cheap ingredients such as high-fructose corn syrup, palm oil, and highly processed flour has caused an increase in the average number of calories people consume each day. Between 1977 and 1995, this increase was nearly two hundred calories! This situation emphasizes the need for us to be aware of our food choices and understand how they can affect our health and overall well-being. Making informed decisions about what we eat is essential for leading a healthy lifestyle and ensuring that we take care of our bodies. By learning more about nutrition and the ingredients in our food, we can make better choices that support our health and help us feel our best. Cooking can be a fun and creative way to explore different flavors and ingredients while also taking care of ourselves. Let's embrace the journey of becoming well-informed cooks and make choices that nourish our bodies and minds.\nContext recap: EPILOGUE: The Well-Informed Cook. Cooking has played a crucial role in shaping our diets and has led to the development of a large food industry. Many of the popular foods that are made in big factories today often receive criticism because they tend to be low in important nutrients and high in unhealthy ingredients like fat, salt, and sugar. Even though these foods are often looked down upon, they are actually what our bodies have learned to crave over time.\nWhy this matters: EPILOGUE The Well-Informed Cook Cooking launched a dietary c helps learners in Anthropology connect ideas from Catching Fire: How Cooking Made Us Human to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
